This is something I've suggested to the team and would like to get feedback from the community on. It's too long and needs me to send it in multiple parts.

Part 1:
Rapido and I had discussed implementing simultaneous hashcat challenges of the same difficulty. This may be more effective as the amount of VRAM per GPU affects how many challenges can be loaded at once. The tradeoff is the hashing speed gets split between all the challenges, so the solving time will take a lot longer. A 4090 will still be able to solve challenges faster than an H100 since it has better hashing speed and will have less challenges loaded to it with 24GB vs 80GB. The maximum difficulty would also have to be brought down, I'm sure (likely no higher than 9 or 10), as 12s would be nearly impossible to solve simultaneously. The scoring mechanism will have to put a large weight on the number of challenges solved, but still account for the average solve speed and the difficulty of the challenges. We don't want to have a situation where people are renting older/slower GPUs that are worse for compute but can load a bunch of challenges into them and still get a high overall score.

With this type of solution implemented, the way challenges are loaded to GPUs will need to be changed. The challenges need to be loaded to one GPU at a time, fill that GPU up, and then move to the next one. Hashcat throws an out of VRAM error when there's no more space to load challenges. We can probably capture this with a try-except statement or the subprocess return code. Upon the challenge failing to load to the GPU, we then start loading the next GPU up.

Part 2:
I've outlined 3 potential options to determine how many challenges to send to miners:
A) We send an arbitrary amount of challenges (enough to fill up 8x H100s, for example) to all miners regardless of their specs and score them based on how many are solved, how fast they're solved, and the challenge difficulties. If we choose option A, miners will optimize their systems to cycle back through the GPUs once all GPUs are loaded up, thus allowing them to load more challenges to them once they've solved the initial challenges. If we go with option A, we should implement the cycling functionality by default to even the playing field for miners.

B) We send a defined number of challenges to each miner based on the specs of the system (aka the GPU models, how many GPUs they have, and the total VRAM). This will limit the ability of miners to cycle through the GPUs again as there be a lower amount of challenges to load into the GPUs as compared to doing the maximum amount to fill 8xH100s. We can change the number of challenges according to the difficulty and GPU models/quantities.

C) Start each miner out at a specific number of challenges and scale the quanity up based on if they solve all challenges or not. This will also have to be on a per-difficulty basis. Meaning, miner 150 might receive 25 difficulty 8 challenges but only 20 difficulty 9 challenges before they fail to solve them all. It would go something like this: send 20 difficulty 8 challenges, if they solve them all then send 21, then 22, then 23, and so on until they reach the terminal point or move up to the next difficulty, whichever comes first. If we do it this way, we'd have to determine challenge difficulty based on a success percentage of how many were solved out of the total challenges sent. It's also important that the immunity period can still account for getting to the highest difficulty if your system is capable of it.

The process for multiple challenges being scored would be something like this:
1) Validators generate Challenge objects (these contain the challenge parameters similar to what I did with the benchmarking tool). These objects are then appended to a list of x length, where x is determined by which method (A, B, C, or something else) we choose to use.

2) Miners receive the list of challenges and process them in parallel using hashcat sessions. Each GPU's total hashrate is split between all the concurrent challenges, so we'd need to take this into account with the difficulties. First we load GPU 1, then GPU 2, and so on until they're all full or we run out of challenges to load. Consider cycling back through the GPUs after the last GPU is loaded with challenges to see if more can be loaded onto them. Miners will likely do this themselves anyway to optimize their output.

3) The miner solves/fails the challenges, generating Result objects (with properties such as the hashcat result, local solve time, and any error messages) which are then placed into a list that's the same length as the Challenge object list received by the validator, and at the same index as the challenge which generated the result.

4) The miner returns the list of Result objects to the validator, who then scores the miner accordingly. The validator can easily check the results as Results[i] should be proportional to Challenges[i] since the lengths are the same and the results are loaded into the same indices as the challenges they're from.
